\chapter{Executive Summary}

Of {{ stats.booksScanned }} books identified by parents and advocacy groups across the country as sexually explicit, age-inappropriate, or ideologically harmful to children, nearly half---{{ stats.booksFound }} titles, totaling {{ total_copies | format_number }} copies---sit on the shelves of Texas public libraries today. This report is the first systematic accounting of where they are.

We queried the public-facing catalogs of 260 Texas library systems. The search is comprehensive: every holding reported here was confirmed by the library's own catalog, not inferred or estimated. This report replaces vague assurances from library administrators with hard data.

\subsection*{A Note on Scope}

This report does not argue that every harmful book should be removed from every library. It does not argue that public libraries should refrain from carrying controversial material for adult readers. It argues something narrower and, we believe, more important: that parents have a right to know what is on the shelves of the institutions to which they send their children, and that the data, presented clearly, speaks for itself.

